Calling China "a true friend that can be trusted," Vanuatuan President Tallis Obed Moses said he is looking to push for further development in Vanuatu-China relationship under the basis of one-China principle. Moses made the remarks during his meeting with visiting Chinese State Councilor and Foreign Minister Wang Yi on Wednesday. Wang is currently on a 10-day in the Pacific region. This year marks the 40th anniversary since the two countries established diplomatic relations, as Wang pointed out. He said the ties has been consolidated through the past four decades, and both sides will continue to "march forward" toward the right direction. China is willing to work with Vanuatu in summarizing the successful experience of exchanges between the two countries and promote China-Vanuatu comprehensive strategic partnership, Wang said. The Chinese diplomat reiterated the importance of mutual respect through country-to-country negotiations and vowed to preserve the legitimate rights of developing countries. 5-point consensus reached On the same day, Wang also met with Vanuatu's Prime Minister Bob Loughman and other major officials from the country in a collective meeting, where they reached a five-point consensus on improving bilateral relations and boosting cooperation in international and regional affairs. The two sides agreed to further strengthen political mutual trust, uphold win-win cooperation with mutual benefit, further friendship between the two peoples, deepen strategic coordination and boost regional cooperation. Wang is on a visit to Vanuatu as part of his tour to the Pacific island countries, which will also take him to Papua New Guinea and Timor Leste. Before arriving in Port Vila, he visited the Solomon Islands, Kiribati, Samoa, Fiji and Tonga. (With input from Xinhua) (Cover: Chinese State Councilor and Foreign Minister Wang Yi (5th L) meets with Vanuatu's Prime Minister Bob Loughman (6th L) in Port Vila, Vanuatu, June 1, 2022. /Chinese Foreign Ministry)